{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0bfc02da-ecac-4cf6-94af-6d60b5e7cb01","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n**Why:**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK version. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the *same* versions of workloads that are already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions to match a new SDK.\n\n**Recommended steps:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, check `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) workloads are present and match your target SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9117c6d5-6972-4b09-b0dc-848951ee8ca8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase for this.","outputTokens":252,"requestId":"E83D:2827DA:24F0021:28F56A3:69F93E27"},"id":"0a6c0d1a-aeb6-49b3-92b7-43cb317129f3","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:47:41.828Z","parentId":"e84e1dfa-f89c-4e36-85c2-af49f20ee38c"}
